T1  - The effect of seasonal adjustment filters on tests for a unit root
AU  - Ghysels, Eric
AU  - Perron, Pierre
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 55
IS  - 1
SP  - 57
EP  - 98
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(93)90004-O
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769390004O
AB  - We consider the effect of seasonal adjustment filters in univariate dynamic models. We concentrate our analysis on the behavior of the least-squares estimator of the sum of the autoregressive coefficients in a regression. We show the existence of a limiting upward bias with the X-11 filter when the process does not contain a unit root. We quantify the extent of this bias for a range of models and filtering procedures. The asymptotic bias has interesting implications with respect to the power of tests for a unit root. In order to assess the importance of this effect we present an extensive simulation study of both the size and power of the usual Dickey-Fuller (1979) and Phillips-Perron (1988) statistics. We show that, in many cases, there is considerable reduction in power compared to the benchmark cases where the data is unfiltered. Finally some practical implications of our study are addressed with respect to tests for unit roots with seasonally adjusted data.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The importance of seasonality in inventory models: Evidence from business survey data
AU  - Nerlove, Marc
AU  - Ross, David
AU  - Willson, Douglas
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 55
IS  - 1
SP  - 105
EP  - 128
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(93)90006-Q
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769390006Q
AB  - The importance of seasonality in inventory models is examined using categorical data from a survey of Swiss manufacturing firms. Survey responses concerning expected new orders and production allow us to directly examine whether firms use inventories to smooth seasonal movements in demand without making strong assumptions concerning a model of firm behavior. We also investigate the importance of seasonality in estimated reduced formrelationships for firm production plans, and compare self-seasonal adjustment procedures, where firms are asked to correct their responses for seasonality, with statistical adjustment procedures that are analogous to dummy variable procedures. The results suggest seasonality does not play a significant role in the production and inventory decisions of Swiss manufacturing firms.
ER  - 

